## S

Single responsibility principle tell us that the one system item must have only one main role and one reason to change.  
It helps change the component independently of other system parts without affecting another system parts.

## O

Open for extensions, closed for modifications.  
This principle help us to prevent breaking changes in other places of use current component.

## L

Liskov principle: A sub-class must be substitutable for its super-class  
That means child classes can be replaced with parent classes without breaking application.

## I

Interface Segregation Principle That means we should implement short concise interfaces instead of huge interfaces with unneccessary dependenices and coupling.

## D

Dependency inversion Extremely useful for implementing low-coupled and modular systems and testing. The Dependency Inversion Principle means that the high level modules in an application should not depend on the low level modules; both should rather depend on abstractions. IOC and Dependency Injection as a ways to use this principle. Example: is very useful in unit testing and implementing low-coupled and modular systems.
